      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(usage): remove argsMenu: auto from /usage command to fix Telegram toggle",
        "body": "## Problem\n`/usage` command registered with `argsMenu: \"auto\"`, causing Telegram to misinterpret the command as having sub-commands and toggle behavior incorrectly.\n\nFixes #93905\n\n## Root Cause\n`resolveCommandArgMenu` returns `null` when args are present, but bare `/usage` triggers broken menu behavior because `argsMenu: \"auto\"` was set in the built-in command registration.\n\n## Fix\nRemove `argsMenu: \"auto\"` from the built-in `/usage` command registration in `src/auto-reply/commands-registry.shared.ts`. The native command name (`usage`) and handler remain in place. The `/usage full` path with explicit mode argument still works correctly because it bypasses the menu.\n\n## Real Behavior Proof\n\n- **Behavior addressed**: `/usage` command incorrectly shows a sub-command toggle in Telegram when typed without arguments. Removing `argsMenu: \"auto\"` restores direct command execution.\n- **Real environment tested**: Linux (Node.js 22), openclaw development checkout with pnpm, vitest 4.1.8.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch**: `node ./node_modules/.bin/vitest run --config test/vitest/vitest.auto-reply.config.ts src/auto-reply/commands-registry.test.ts`\n- **Evidence after fix**:\n```\n$ node ./node_modules/.bin/vitest run --config test/vitest/vitest.auto-reply.config.ts src/auto-reply/commands-registry.test.ts\n\n RUN  v4.1.8 /home/user/openclaw\n\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  31 passed (31)\n   Start at  10:57:48\n   Duration  7.71s (transform 3.80s, setup 698ms, import 6.05s, tests 697ms, environment 0ms)\n```\n- **Observed result after fix**: All 31 command registry tests pass. The `/usage` command registration no longer includes `argsMenu`, and Telegram clients will not show a sub-command toggle for the bare `/usage` command. The `/usage full` variant continues to work with explicit mode argument.\n- **What was not tested**: Full Telegram round-trip with a real bot was not manually tested; the fix only changes command registration metadata (removing one field) so the risk of Telegram-specific behavioral issues is minimal.",
